Narrative Log
Dev Log - 2026-05-30

This was a truth-surface day. The work did not expand the product in a visible way; it tightened the language that defines what the product is allowed to mean right now. In a repo like this, that matters. When architecture notes drift, the team starts inheriting false confidence, and the boundary between “implemented” and “supported” gets blurry fast.

The central change was a refresh of docs/architecture/00-current-state.md. That file is the short-form release contract for the repo, and today it was brought back into alignment with the current week’s actual main work. The update reflects the Guardian delegation and campaign-runner plumbing that landed recently, along with the Whooshd provider metadata now present in the local catalog/config path. But the important discipline is what the file did not say: it did not inflate those changes into a wider release promise.

That distinction was the real work. The docs now name the new pieces, but they also keep the fence in place. End-to-end delegation is still not treated as release-supported. Federation is still treated as high-blast-radius. Graph writes are still not being casually pulled into the supported path. The file is doing what it should do: describing the system as it is, not as it would be convenient to claim it is.

I also updated the architecture README so the current-state doc is framed as this week’s live operational truth and priority set. That is a small change, but it helps keep the navigation layer honest. When people land in the architecture docs, they should be able to find the current contract quickly and understand that it is the active interpretation layer, not just another static reference.

The deeper shift here is subtle but important. The system did not become more feature-rich today. It became more legible. It became harder to mistake in-progress delegation work for shipped runtime behavior. It became easier to tell what is actually supported on the local-only path and what still needs proof before it can be widened. That is the kind of change that prevents future confusion.

What this makes possible next is straightforward: keep the release-truth docs synced with the live main posture, and only widen the support story when the runtime proof is actually there.

